@node "features" "What does it do?"

   Plain and simple, it allows you to grab the speech output
   from your Amiga, and save it as a standard 8svx/iff sample
   or a standard 8bit mono wav sample.

   It has a nice GUI, using standard gadtools and ReqTools.

   The generated samples can then be used in your Mods, on your
   Web site, in games, or anything else you can think of.

   You can, of course, re-edit the samples in your favorite
   sample editor or music program.

   Oh, I almost forgot - it's fashionable to brag that a program
   doesn't cause any Enforcer hits.

   So: 

        *** This program causes no Enforcer hits! ***


   Actually, the truth is that no program should ever cause 
   an Enforcer hit.
@endnode

@node "requirements" "What do I need?"

  This program requires at least v2.xx of the OS

  You also must have the ReqTools.library installed
  If you don't have ReqTools, you can find it on 
  Aminet.  I didn't bother including it here, since
  it has been distributed with so many programs over
  the years that I would imagine everybody already
  has it by now  ;)

  MOST IMPORTANT OF ALL:

  This program will NOT work unless you have a working
  speech setup on your Amiga.  Either the WB 1.xx version
  or the WB 2.xx versions will do.  

  If you are not sure, or don't understand what I mean, 
  see the @{" Amiga Speech " link "Aspeech" 0} section.

  Also note that the "Say" command MUST be found in
  your SYS:Utilities/  drawer.  Just having it somewhere
  in your PATH is not good enough...

  I have heard that "Say" is sometimes found in SYS:c/
  rather than in SYS:utilities/.  If this is the case
  on your system, you will need to put a copy of "Say"
  into SYS:utilities/.  This is the only place that the
  Say2Raw command will find it.
@endnode

@node "install" "Installation"

 Installation is simply a matter of dropping the
 entire Speak2Sample drawer wherever you want.

 If you get an error requester when you try to
 run the program, see the @{" Amiga Speech " link "Aspeech" 0} section.

 Just don't remove the Say2Raw command from the
 drawer.  It must be kept in the same drawer as
 Speak2Sample. And don't change the name of
 Say2Raw.

 It is OK to change the name of Speak2Sample.
@endnode

@node "Aspeech" "About Amiga speech..."

  Versions 1.xx and 2.xx of the Amiga OS shipped with speech 
  capability built in.  Unfortunately, version 3.xx did not 
  include these programs.

  Both versions do work fine on OS 3.xx, if you can find a
  copy of the required programs.  If you ever had OS 1.3 ~ 2.04
  just dig out your old WB disks, and copy the programs over
  to the proper directories as explained below.

  If not, sorry, but you're on your own.

  I can not distribute these programs - they are copyrighted to 
  Commodore (or GateWay now, I imagine) so don't ask.

  Here is what you will need and where it goes:

  SYS:l/           Speak-handler
  SYS:libs/        translator.library
  SYS:devs/        narrator.device
  SYS:utilities/   Say


  Speak-handler  should be mounted at boot time to avoid problems.
                 I have been told that it not needed on some systems,
                 but I get severe fast memory trashing without it.


  translator.library  translates normal text into the "phenomes"
                      that are needed by the narrator.device

  narrator.device  does the actual "speaking"

  Say   is a command line program that allows you to enter plain
        text which is then translated and spoken.  You must have
        the actual Say program from the WB disks.  I have tried
        several programs on Aminet that claim to be updated re-
        placements for "Say".  THEY ARE NOT!  They are all really
        replacements for "SpeechToy", which is a GUI version of Say.
        They are all quite nice, but they won't work for our
        purposes.

@endnode

@node "use" "What do I do with it?"


  OK, the program is actually pretty self-explanatory, so
  no one will ever read this.  But just in case:

  The string gadget at the top is where you type in the
  text that you want to have spoken.

  Just below are cycle gadgets for "Male/Female" voice
  selection and "Natural/Robot" intonation.

  To the right are sliders for rate and pitch.  Just
  experiment with these to see what they do to the voice.

  At the bottom is the Record button, IFF/WAV output selector,
  a Test button and a Quit button.

 
  To use, first enter the text you want spoken.
  Use the cycle gadget to select the save format, either IFF
  or WAV.
  Then, use the controls to set up the voice the way you like.
  Press the "Test" button at any time to hear the Amiga speak
  your text without recording it to a disk file.

  When you are happy with how it sounds, press the "Record"
  button.  You will get a standard ASL file-requester so you
  can specify where you want the sample saved, and give it a
  name.  Then the text will be "spoken", Say2Raw will capture
  the output in a raw data file, and Speak2Sample will convert
  this into a standard iff or wav file, and save it to disk.

  That's all there is to it.

  If you have any questions or problems, or just want to say
  "thanks" for the program, write @{" me " link "contact" 0}
@endnode

